    <h2>CandleStick Patterns</h2>
    <p>
Candlestick patterns help traders understand market sentiment
by showing how buyers and sellers behaved during a time period.
They are formed using OHLC data and often signal trend continuation or reversal.
</p>

<h5>1. Doji</h5>
<p>
A Doji forms when the open and close prices are nearly the same.
It indicates <strong>indecision</strong> in the market and often appears
near trend reversals.
</p>

<h5>2. Marubozu</h5>
<p>
A Marubozu has no upper or lower wick, indicating strong momentum.
A bullish Marubozu shows full buyer control, while a bearish one shows seller dominance.
</p>
<h5>3. Hammer</h5>
<p>
A Hammer appears after a downtrend with a small body and long lower wick.
It shows that buyers stepped in after heavy selling pressure.
</p>

<h5>4. Shooting Star</h5>
<p>
A Shooting Star forms after an uptrend with a small body and long upper wick.
It suggests sellers are gaining control and a possible downside reversal.
</p>



<p class="text-muted">
Candlestick patterns work best when combined with volume and trend analysis.
</p>


